  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most countries. It typically falls under criminal legislation and financial crime statutes. Money laundering involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, usually by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear legal. Many countries have specific anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations with significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Substantial fines\n2. Imprisonment\n3. Asset seizure\n4. Criminal prosecution\n\nThe specific legal details and penalties can vary by jurisdiction, but money laundering is generally considered a serious criminal activity.",
